recordings.rmk: recorded with Sony PCM M10 + EM172 capsules + telinga parabolic dish

A flock of purely Tundra swans coming in to their roost during the evening twilight. All members of the flock were visually identified. I followed the flock with a parabolic microphone as they flew by, over a landscape probably also used by whooper swans for roosting. Birds on the ground were hidden, so there might also be calls from whooper swans on the ground in the recording. At the end it can be heard how the tundra swans land on a water surface (the woosh of the water can be heard) on the other end of the area (invisible to the observer) and start social interactions.
The area is a turf mining complex beeing partly rewetted and renatured. The swans, bean geese and cranes use the water surfaces in the renaturing areas for roosting.
the recording is intended to convey the impression of distant birds

Very calm winter day (about 2 °C, no sun), a great part of the polder was flooded. Because of cold nights there was some ice, too. A group of whooper swans was already present (together with other water fowl), when other whooper swans arrived. Four swans (partly from the newly arrived birds) were singing together for four minutes, standing in shallow water, moving heads, necks and wings slowly. Then this small group dissolved. The recording was not modified.

Intervals between the song phrases shortened  to cut out noise from handling the microphone.
